<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-627-544  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 627 544.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 10 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Santa Cruz Operation acquiring Canada's HCR.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Santa Cruz Operation Inc. (acquisitions and mergers)HCR Corp. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Topic:     Computer software industryStrategic PlanningAcquisitionSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SANTA CRUZ OPERATION ACQUIRING CANADA'S HCR SANTA CRUZ, CALIFORNIA, U.S.A.,andO;1990 MAY 8 (NB) -- The Santa Cruz Operation (SCO), maker of the leading Unixsystem software for Intel-based microcomputers, has announced plans toacquire a major Canadian Unix system software developer, HCR Corporation ofToronto.andM;SCO says HCR, famous for such products as HCR/C++, an object-orientedprogramming language, and dbXtra an advanced debugging and programdevelopment tool, will run as an independent subsidiary company, and willchange its name to SCO Canada, Inc. HCR will take over SCO's Canadiancustomer base.andM;The transaction is subject to completion of legal review and finalshareholder approval.andM;SCO President Larry Michels says SCO will benefit by gaining strength inprogramming tools, particularly under Open Desktop, its complete graphicaloperating system for 386 and 486 computers.andP;  He says the company will alsoincrease its ability to supply corporate contract-development services andconsulting and will gain a presence in Canada.andM;HCR President Michael Tilson said, &quot;We are delighted to join with SCO.andP;  We'vealways had superb abilities in Unix System software development andprogramming tools.andP;  By aligning ourselves with the world's market leader inopen-system software, we vastly increase our scope.&quot;andM;Tilson will continue to head the Toronto operation while becoming a vicepresident of SCO.andP;  HCR's existing management structure will remain in place,and all current employees will retain their positions.andP;  Significant expansionof all groups in Toronto is likely in the coming year, according to SantaCruz Operation.andM;HCR provides custom Unix System software development services to majorclients, including IBM, Intel, and other major computer manufacturers.andM;Detailed financial terms of the acquisition were not announced.andP;  Companyofficials said that the transaction would consist of a share swap with amulti-million dollar value.andM;(Wendy Woods/19900508)</TEXT></DOC>